{"questionId":"22702","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Irina uses a set of coordinate axes to draw her design of a window. The base of the window&nbsp;is on the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis, the upper part of the window is in the form of a quadratic curve and the sides&nbsp;are vertical lines, as shown on the diagram. The curve has end points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;and its vertex is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>)</mo></math>. Distances are measured in centimetres.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/72673af2267722130ff9ee50373a52e7974f1d1e.png\"></p>\n<p>The quadratic curve can be expressed in the form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>8</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence form two equations in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>64</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for each equivalent expression or <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for the use of the axis of symmetry formula to find&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;or from use of derivative.&nbsp;&nbsp;Award <em><strong>A0A1</strong></em> for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>64</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math>.<br><br></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22702","referenceCode":"21N.1.SL.TZ0.13a.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence form two equations in terms of a and b.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.5—Modelling functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}